                                <p> By Pritha Sarkar</p>
                                <p> LONDON, Sept 23 (Reuters) - Former French Open champion  Michael Chang could be making his final appearance at the Hong  Kong Open this week when he takes on fourth seed Alex Corretja  in the first round.</p>
                                <p> The three-times winner of the tournament, handed a wildcard  for the event since his ranking has plummeted to 118, has made  no secret during the season that his playing days on the ATP  tour are numbered.</p>
                                <p> With the 30-year-old Chang having enjoyed huge popularity in  Asia throughout his career, the American said he was looking  forward to his 12th and possibly last outing in Hong Kong.</p>
                                <p> "This probably could be the last time that I will be playing  in Hong Kong," said Chang, who can expect thunderous backing  when he steps on court for his clash against Spaniard Corretja.</p>
                                <p> "This city has treated me well over the years and I hope  this tournament will be great for me," he said.     </p>
                                <p> "Retirement is definitely on the cards. The passion is still  there but it is becoming more and more difficult to win  tournaments," added the 1989 Roland Garros winner.</p>
                                <p> Chang desperately wants to end his title drought -- since  his victory in Los Angeles in 2000 -- before hanging up his  racket.</p>
                                <p> Although Chang has split his time this season between the  lower Challenger circuit and the main Tour, Pete Sampras's  success at the the U.S. Open earlier this month after a two-year  barren spell definitely provides hope for the player once ranked  world number two.</p>
                                <p> "I don't know what the future holds. I may not win another  match but it's important for me to walk away knowing that I gave  it my all," said Chang, who captured the Calabasas Challenger by  defeating compatriot Cecil Mamiit in April. </p>
                                <p> "I do think about retirement but there is a belief in my  heart that there are better days for me tennis-wise.</p>
                                <p> "That's my hope. My hope is that there are better things in  store for me."</p>
                                <p> With the ATP bandwagon moving on to Tokyo next week, the  next few days could provide the last opportunity for fans in  Asia to capture a glimpse of Chang on court.  </p>
